                text: "### Data Analysis Report\n\nBased on the survey results provided, here is an analysis of the current passenger experience:\n\n#### **Key Trends**\n*   **Primary User Base:** The majority of respondents (55%) utilize the **East-West Line**.\n*   **Critical Pain Point (Temperature):** There is an overwhelming consensus regarding thermal comfort. **89% of respondents (8 out of 9)** reported the cabins are \"Too Warm.\" Notably, nobody selected \"Comfortable.\"\n*   **Infrastructure Engagement:** Passengers highly value navigational and stability aids. The **Dynamic Route Map Display** and **Grab Poles** are the most utilized features, suggesting that passengers prioritize directional clarity and physical stability during transit.\n\n#### **Summary of Text Feedback**\nThe qualitative data confirms a strong demand for climate control improvements. While general sentiment regarding cleanliness and service is positive, there is a clear divide based on external conditions:\n*   **Climate Sensitivity:** A significant portion of feedback (including multilingual responses in Chinese, Malay, and Tamil) highlights that the current air-conditioning is insufficient to combat Singapore’s heat.\n*   **Operational Nuance:** One passenger suggested a reduction in fan speed during cooler early morning hours, indicating that a \"one-size-fits-all\" temperature setting may not be ideal.\n*   **Maintenance/Environment:** There is a specific request for brighter ambient lighting in older train models to improve the overall interior atmosphere.\n\n---\n\n### **Actionable Recommendations**\n\n1.  **Dynamic Climate Control Adjustment:**\n    Implement a climate control protocol that adjusts cabin temperatures based on real-time external weather data and peak-hour passenger density. Since feedback indicates midday cabins feel \"stuffy\" when crowded, increasing the cooling intensity during peak heat hours (12 PM – 4 PM) is essential to improve passenger satisfaction.\n\n